The Nautilus Development Team is preparing for a major update to their database infrastructure. 
To ensure a smooth transition and to safeguard data, the team has requested the DevOps team to take a snapshot of the current RDS instance and restore it to a new instance. 
This process is crucial for testing and validation purposes before the update is rolled out to the production environment. 
The snapshot will serve as a backup, and the new instance will be used to verify that the backup process works correctly and that the application can function seamlessly with the restored data.

As a member of the Nautilus DevOps Team, your task is to perform the following:
Take a Snapshot: Take a snapshot of the xfusion-rds RDS instance and name it xfusion-snapshot (please wait xfusion-rds instance to be in available state).
Restore the Snapshot: Restore the snapshot to a new RDS instance named xfusion-snapshot-restore.
Configure the New RDS Instance: Ensure that the new RDS instance has a class of db.t3.micro.

Verify the New RDS Instance: The new RDS instance must be in the Available state upon completion of the restoration process.

Step 1: Take a Snapshot of the Existing RDS Instance
Login to AWS Console:
Go to AWS Management Console and log in.
Navigate to RDS:
In the top search bar, type RDS and select RDS.
Select the RDS Instance:
Go to Databases in the left-hand menu.
Select the RDS instance named xfusion-rds.
Ensure the status is Available before taking a snapshot.
Take a Snapshot:
Click Actions > Take snapshot.
Snapshot name: Enter xfusion-snapshot.
Click Take Snapshot.
Wait for the snapshot status to change to Available. This may take a few minutes.

Step 2: Restore the Snapshot to a New RDS Instance
Go to Snapshots:
In the left-hand menu, click Snapshots.
Locate the snapshot xfusion-snapshot you just created.
Restore the Snapshot:
Select the snapshot and click Actions > Restore snapshot.
In the Restore DB Instance page:
DB Instance Identifier: Enter xfusion-snapshot-restore.
DB Instance Class: Select db.t3.micro.
Configure other settings as needed (VPC, subnet, security groups, storage, etc.).
Click Restore DB Instance.
Wait for Restoration:
The new RDS instance (xfusion-snapshot-restore) will be created.
Monitor the status under Databases. Wait until it is Available.

Step 3: Verify the New RDS Instance
Check Availability:
Go to Databases, and locate xfusion-snapshot-restore.
Ensure the Status shows Available.
Test Connectivity (Optional):
Use a database client or connect via the AWS Console Query Editor to verify the database is working correctly.
Notes on Configuration
Ensure that the VPC, subnets, and security groups allow connectivity if you need to connect to the new RDS instance from EC2 or your local machine.
The restored RDS instance retains the data and configuration from the snapshot.
Using db.t3.micro ensures a low-cost, test-friendly instance type for validation.
